			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Well, I'm tossing in the towel.  This game's just not worth my time any longer.
<br />

<br />
I've followed my discontent with the game back to it's source, and the source is Sony.  Luclin began the trend (quibble if you want), and POP cemented it.  You MUST have a large guild of 200+ to succeed at the top end.  After a fling with LDON, the uberguilders complained about lack of content, so Sony created GoD, in which only Elemental guilds have a chance of succeeding.   They may be smaller raids, but if you have to have the 72 to get into Elementals and succeed, and you need to be successful in EL to succeed in GoD, then the fix is in.  I bitched about this somewhat about the timd GoD came out, but got about the reception I expected from this board.  /shrug.
<br />

<br />
Large guilds mean tons of time and effort devoted to keeping them together, as you all know.  In short, this is "<span style="font-weight: bold">game overhead</span>." The things you<span style="font-weight: bold"> have </span>to do in order to do the things you <span style="font-weight: bold">want</span> to do.
<br />

<br />
Some people thrive on that; they find the challenge of running a guild to be more fun than the game itself. They relish the challenge.  I do not--<span style="font-style: italic">I want to play the damn game.</span>   Therefore, the concept of game overhead is an absurdity and anathma to me.  I've clashed with people here that disagree, but I'm more detached about that now. With the alternatives out there, there's a game for every niche, and I've selected one to be my new MMORPG addiction.   Let EQ continue to be the game for uberguilds.  But don't pretend that it's really for everyone, it literally cannot be.
<br />

<br />
The alternative, were I to stay in EQ, is to be on the other end of the equation.  Resign as officer in LS, or go to a new guild and be Enchanter #23.  Not be an officer or have any responsibilties.  But that runs against my grain also.  I'd be one of the people creating the overhead, rather than working on it.  I don't have to<span style="font-style: italic"> try </span>to create it, I do by just being there: tracking my DKP, raid leaders deciding where to put me, running a forum for me to post on, doing a website, etc..  I can't consume people's time without giving back (it's not in my personality), and giving back takes away from time to enjoy the game.  That's insane to me.  Worse, despite some lingering bitterness about certain ex-member's actively recruiting from LS (near 15% of your guild's roster is ex-LS, you know who you are), it's an inevitability that such was going to happen.   Not just to us, or even in the past *by* us, but to anyone anywhere. 
<br />

<br />
Why is all this crap necessary to play the damn game? 
<br />

<br />
Because Sony ensured you must have 72 people to succeed in key raids, which means you need to teach a couple hundred to whistle Dixie together.  Over 4,000 of the 24k+ posts on the LS boards are mine.  I don't live on boards and PL my count for the hell of it, like some people do, so I think that says a lot about how much work I've put in since being a founding officer of LS back in Dec, 2001.  Much of it was in trying to reach that level and teach people to whistle Dixie.
<br />

<br />
And I don't agree with a design philosophy that requires that sort of time and effort.  This is the base reason why I'm closing accounts (or letting friends have them), and leaving the game, rather than apping another guild.  Lunar Shadows' recent collapse as a planar guild is the <span style="font-style: italic">immediate</span> reason, but that stems directly from the fact that to be a planar, hell, elemental guild, we have to spend too much time and effort doing things other than opening up a can o' whoopass like we know how.
<br />

<br />
And I just can't do that any more. I can't enjoy the game without the ability to play with friends and WIN, and I can't win without spending a lot of time actually NOT playing the game, but dealing with the overhead instead.  Specificlaly being there to help them rebuild the guild a third time.  Things you do because you have to do them are called jobs.
<br />

<br />
My final wishes are for Lunar Shadows to prosper and regrow.  It's got some fine leaders, officers, and members, and I'm damn glad to have been a member, and for a while, their leader. It's only weakness is that it never had a recruiter worth the title.  Still, I recommend it to anyone desiring a casual raiding guild with a family touch.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
